This paper is likely to belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category as it involves the development of a clickbait detection model that uses distributed sub-word embeddings learned from a large corpus. Additionally, the paper also involves the analysis of user engagement with clickbait and non-clickbait contents, which could fall under the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. The paper also involves the study of the distribution of topics in clickbait and non-clickbait contents, which could fall under the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category. The use of machine learning models and large-scale data analysis could also make this paper relevant to the Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-category. Finally, the paper's focus on analyzing media practices could also make it relevant to the Sound and Music Computing (cs.SD) sub-category, which involves the analysis of media content.
